## Background 

This is a short version of Durham's Python tutorial for new astronomy
PhD students and all STFC CDT students.

I wrote the course from scratch last year and trialled it with ~10
Astronomy students. This year, same course was given to >25 students from
astronomy and particle physics.  

9 hours: 6 hours of getting to grips with Python and setting some challenge
problems, a couple of weeks to absorb and practice, followed by a further 3
hours of review, questions and astronomy-specific material. 

???

The course is intended to expose students to the range of material and make
sure everyone is at a level sufficient to get value from practicing in other
graduate courses.

---

## Why learn Python? 

- Get stuff done faster!
- Make beautiful plots!
- Use one tool for everything!
- Take advantage of a huge library of third-party code!

---

## Why learn Python? 

There are always realistic alternatives, but:

- If you want a job in astronomy, you *should* learn Python. The more you know
  the better for your career, but you will get by with basic knowledge. 

- If you want a job in industrial Data Science you almost certainly *must*
  learn Python, and should be proactive about constantly improving your
  skills. You also need a sound working knowledge of other major languages.

- Python is the glue for data science: even if you specialize in a different
  language, you will not be able to avoid Python in day-to-day interactions
  with your colleagues.

- Python expertise may be the single most valuable transferable skill you
  acquire in your PhD - and almost certainly the easiest to demonstrate.

???

Don't worry, because Python is extremely easy to learn.

---

## Learning Python 

Teaching yourself Python is easy enough once you get started - you can to do
most of the work on your own, using resources your find for yourself online.
This is how most professional programmers learn.

- Following tutorials is a good way to get started.
- The only reliable way to improve is through trial and error.
- Try to do everyday computing tasks with Python, even if it takes a bit longer at first.
- Look for fast solutions, but also short and elegant ones (eventually second nature).
- Read books and other people's code.
- Get into the habit of writing neat, self-explanatory programs with lots of comments.

---

- Python in a nutshell

## Python in a nutshell

Wikipedia:

<font color='gray'> Python is a <font color='green'><b>high-level</b></font> programming language used for <font color='green'><b>general-purpose</b></font>
 programming and originally created by Guido van Rossum in 1991. Python has a
 design philosophy which <font color='green'><b>emphasizes code readability</b></font>, and a syntax which
 allows programmers to <font color='green'><b>express concepts in fewer lines of code</b></font> than
 possible in languages such as C++ or Java. The language provides constructs
 intended to enable writing <font color='green'><b>clear programs on both a small and large
 scale</b></font>.  </font>
 
 Python features a <font color='green'><b>dynamic type system</b></font> and <font color='green'><b>automatic memory management</b></font>
 and supports multiple programming paradigms, including object-oriented,
 imperative, functional programming, and procedural styles. It has a <font color='green'><b>large
 and comprehensive standard library</b></font>.

???

Python is a language that lets you express yourself clearly, but it doesn't force you do that.

Other languages might make code shorter or claim to make large programs more
robust at the expense of being readable, for example by forcing you to say
explicitly how many bits there are used to represent every variable, or
defining what every function does separately from the function itself, or when
exactly memory is allocated to your program or freed up. Python makes thinking
about these things optional -- they're there if you want them but to quickly
get stuff done they're kept out of your way.

If Python is your first language you might find it hard to understand why other
languages are so complicated. Very often there's a good reason.

---


## Python code looks like this

```python
wind_speed_knots = 140 # let's say, for example 

if wind_speed_knots < 29:
    print('This is a tropical depression')
elif wind_speed_knots < 55:
    print('This is a tropical storm')
elif wind_speed_knots < 113:
    print('This is a typhoon!')
elif wind_speed_knots > 120:
    print('This is a super typhoon!')
    if not hatches_battened:
        print('Batten down the hatches!')
```
---

### Indentation 

Python statements are grouped into **blocks** (conditions, functions, classes, loops etc.) using **indentation**. The start of a block is
indicated by a `:`. 

<tt><font color='gray'>wind_speed_knots   = 140<br>
if wind_speed_knots < 29<b><font color='red'>:</font></b><br>
<b><font color='red'>>>>></b>print('This is a tropical depression')</font><br>
elif wind_speed_knots > 120<b><font color='blue'>:</font></b><br>
<b><font color='blue'>>>>></b>print('This is a super typhoon!')</font><br>
<b><font color='blue'>>>>></b>if not hatches_battened<b></font><font color='green'>:</font></b><br>
<b><font color='green'>>>>></b><b><font color='green'>>>>></font></b>print('Batten down the hatches!')</font><br>
</font></tt>

By convention these indentations are 4 spaces, ***not*** .mono[.small[TAB]]
characters. Other languages have different ways of indicating blocks (e.g. C
uses `{}`).

---


## What Python is good at

Python is popular with (most) scientists in large part because:

* They prefer solutions that minimize person-time at the cost of algorithmic elegance, computing time and code length
  (they know it's bad to over-optimize).
* They don't like reinventing the wheel and prefer to re-use code (with caution about understanding and trusting it). Python has the best reservoir of good third party code for science of any language.
* They work on multiple things at once, so value readability and prefer to use the minimum number of tools.
* They like that fact that Python can inter-operate with faster, lower-level languages like C and Fortran in a reasonably straightforward way.

???

This leads to a feedback loop -- the more scientists that use a language, the
richer the ecosystem of scientific packages, which encourages more scientists
and raises the barrier to using a different language.

---

## What Python is not so good at

Python is naturally slow if you don't think about how to make it fast. There
are many ways to speed up your Python code (and avoid writing slow code in the first place).

When you've exhausted all the options for speeding up Python, you can still
resort to mixing C, C++ or Fortran into your Python code -- this is not a bad
thing, and Python makes it easy.

Python is rather poor at running multiple processes at once (concurrency) and
hence in making use of machines more powerful than your laptop.  This *can* be
done in a practical way, but it's not a first-class part of Python.

---

There are realistic alternatives to Python plus C/Fortran:

* `IDL`: what astronomers used before they discovered Python. Mostly awful (and closed source, and not free!).
* `R`: slightly nicer equivalent to IDL prioritising statistics, *still* slowly growing in popularity.
* `Rust`: an up-and-coming alternative to C++. 
* `Julia`: a nascent, aggressively trendy language designed from scratch for data science. 
* `Haskell`: a powerful language using the 'functional' style, with a brutal learning curve.

Of course there are many others. Some of the reason for this diversity is in
the 'style' of the languages, not what they are capable of doing or how fast
they can do it.

## The Python environment

From a practical point of view, 'Python' comprises:

- a **language** (rules for translating the stuff you write into instructions the computer understands).

--

- an **interpreter** (`python`) that takes the code you write and runs some computations on your machine.

--

- some **modules**: individual files that contain functions you or others
  have written to do specific jobs, which you can include in new code
  to avoid having to write everything from scratch each time.

--

- **packages** that group modules according to some common
  purpose and means of telling the interpreter where to find all the
  packages that you want to use (the python **environment**).

---

## Python versions

- The Python language has two versions: 2 and 3. In future, Python3 will be the only version.
- Few obvious differences. Most major packages fully support Python3.
- Python3 assumed here, recommend you use that for your own work.

You can check what version of the Python interpreter you're using in a terminal:
```bash
python --version
```

If this tells you you have Python 2, you might still have the option to use
Python 3. Try 
```bash
python3 --version```

---

## Writing and running simple Python scripts

Two basic ways of working:
- Write commands in a `.py` file and run it with `python`
- Start an interactive interpreter and type commands one-by-one (REPL)

---

A Hello World program in python might look like this: `print(Hello World)`

If we put this in `hello.py` and run it with the interpreter, we get:

```
> python hello.py
Hello World!
```

Compare with C:

```C
#include<stdio.h> // Need this for output

main() // Need a 'main' function
{
    printf("Hello World"); // Need a ; to end lines.
} // code in the main function is marked with {}
```

We would need to compile this and then run the resulting executable.

---

## The REPL way of working

The fact that Python is run through an interpreter makes it natural to work
with interactively (i.e. by writing one line at a time, pressing return to
evaluate that line, and looking at the result that gets printed). 

The built-in interactive interpreter (Python shell) that
you get by running `python` with no file argument is the most basic version of
this so-called 'REPL' (read-evaluate-print-loop) way of working with Python. 

Every line you type is passed as a command to the Python interpreter, and then
prints whatever the Python interpreter sends back as the 'result' of the
command. The results of previous lines stay in memory as if they were all being
executed one after the other.

## Running Python with IPython and Jupyter

The REPL way of working with Python is **extremely** useful for two things:

1. Developing more sophisticated codes, by experimenting with different ways of doing things, one step at a time.
1. Using python to explore data, by doing calculations and making plots interactively.

The built-in Python shell is very basic and pretty much useless for either task.

---

**IPython** (interactive Python) is a more advanced interactive prompt, and the
most common way of working interactively with Python.  Many useful
features, including:

* colourful syntax highlighting
* a command history
* interactive help
* interactive plotting
* a way to inspect the state of variables in programs after they cause errors, to find out what happened (debugging)

There are other more fancy 'development environments' that are mostly GUI applications built on top
of IPython.

---

**Juptyer notebooks** are a way of working with IPython in a 'less linear' way
by adding an extra layer of javascript that shows a fancy version of an IPython
session in a web browser.

This makes it easy to organize and document your interactive work so you can
share it with others.

* Great for interactive tutorials!
* Great as a notebook for recording data exploration and developing code.
* Complexity makes it somewhat fragile.
* Awkward if you want to work remotely, especially behind a firewall.
* Ultimately limited to short snippets, debugging more awkward than IPython.

---

There are many tricks for interacting more productively with Jupyter
notebooks and IPython sessions.

* Type `%magic` to learn about 'magic' functions (commands that interact with IPython/Jupyter rather than being interpreted as Python code)
* Run system commands by starting the line with a `!`, e.g. `!ls -lhtr` (but don't try this with commands that require user input or update the display continuously, like `top`)
* Command history: scroll back through previous commands.
* Access the built-in debugger with the `%debug` magic command - an essential productivity boost, once you figure out how to use it. 

---

## Other sources of help

Python help lives in the code itself

The `pydoc` command:
```bash
pydoc str.upper
```

(try `pydoc -k something` to search built-in documentation for 'something'; `pydoc -b` for an html overview of all the packages installed on your machine)

Documentation for the Standard Library packages: [https://docs.python.org/3/library/index.html](https://docs.python.org/3/library/index.html)

A popular question+answer website: 
[http://stackoverflow.com/](stackoverflow.com/)

---

## One last thing: credit and citations

Python is open source, and most of the packages you use will also be open
source. Hundreds of people have put in tremendous effort to make your work
easier. They deserve credit for this.

If you publish papers using Python (even if for plots), cite the packages you
use appropriately where possible, list names/give URLs if nothing else.

### BasicPythonReview.ipynb

This notebook introduces the most basic features of Python.

First a bit more orientation:
* Get familiar with Juptyer and practice basic maths at the Python interactive prompt.
* See how to write comments (and be warned that this is super-important).
* See what happens when your Python code has errors.
* Understand the `print()` command a bit more.

---

### BasicPythonReview.ipynb

Then the serious stuff:
* How variables work
* How to manipulate text ('strings') 
* What the special value `None` is (this is important)
* How boolean logic works
* How to write conditional expressions (`if...else`)
* How to write `while` loops.

These notebooks assume you have done some programming before and are familiar
with ideas like integer and floating point representations of numbers.

---

### CollectionsAndLoops.ipynb

Collections are extremely important. Collections are objects that group other
objects together. The three most important types of collection are `list`,
`tuple` and `dict`. Manipulating these three basic collections is fundamental
to everyday programming in Python.

Usually you want to do something to each element of a list. This involves
iterating (looping) over the elements, so this notebook also shows how `for`
loops work.

---

### DataInDataOut.ipynb

Compared to some other languages, Python makes interacting with data and the
file system very easy. It's possible to replace a lot of what used to be done
with confusing and complicated shell scripts with more elegant Python programs.

This notebook covers:
- opening files and reading lines of text
- creating files and writing lines of text
- processing text files line by line
- storing complex python objects
- other useful formats for large data files
- working with filesystem paths
- finding files with `glob`

---

### FunctionsAndClasses.ipynb

This notebook covers:

* The elements of structure in Python: functions and classes
* Defining functions (including the idea of variable scope, nested functions, lambdas and recursion)
* Defining classes and creating objects

???
Classes can be confusing if you haven't met object-oriented programming before.
Fortunately one of the great things about Python is that it lets you solve
problems in the way you find least confusing. Sometimes this will involve
classes, but only if that approach suits the problem and you. Python doesn't
force you to understand the mechanics or the philosophy of defining your own
classes to write sophisticated programs. 
---

This notebook covers:

* Modules and namespaces
* `import` statements and `PYTHONPATH`

## Python style conventions

Sticking to certain conventions for how to format code makes it easier to share with others and can also have some productivity benefits (helping you to avoid errors and confusion).

The best practice guidelines for Python are called PEP8:
https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/

Once you know what these conventions are, using them becomes increasingly automatic (because you see that everyone else uses them) and eventually makes sense.


---

## Code editors suitable for Python

You can write python programs with the most basic of text editors, but syntax
highlighting and the ability to replace tabs with spaces are more-or-less a
minimum requirement. The most popular Unix editors are `emacs` and `vim` (both
of which work in a terminal as well as being 'normal' windowed applications). 

There are other possibilities if you want 'bells and whistles':
- [Discussion of Python editors](https://www.fullstackpython.com/development-environments.html)
- [Atom](https://atom.io/)
- [SublimeText](http://www.sublimetext.com/)
- [PyCharm](https://www.jetbrains.com/pycharm/)
- [Spyder](https://pythonhosted.org/spyder/)
- [One of many discussions of using Vim for Python](https://www.fullstackpython.com/vim.html)

## Managing Python Packages

*Bottom line: If in doubt use `pip` to install packages, but I recommend
learning how to use `conda`*

`pip` is a tool that install additional Python packages from an online
repository into a standard location on your system. Once you've installed a
package with `pip` you can `import` it in your own code.

`conda` is in some way a more advanced version of `pip`. As well as installing
packages, `conda` can create self-contained 'environments' in which you can
install (Python) software separately from anything else on the system. This has
some advantages when you want one version of a package for one project and
another version for another project, but isn't something you need to worry
about to start with.

---

### Conda/Miniconda/Anaconda

https://conda.io/docs/user-guide/install/index.html

Miniconda and Anaconda are 'distributions' (collections)
of a large number python packages, which rely on `conda`. The distributions
(stored on a server somewhere) provide the packages, and you use the `conda`
tool to manage them. `conda` is not specifically linked to Python.

---

### Pip

`pip` is a simpler idea than `conda`. More or less, `pip` is a tool to install
*only* Python packages. `pip` knows about  one big official archive of Python
packages on the web (rather than the various 'distributions' that conda has
access too). 

Unlike `conda`, `pip` will try to to install packages in a default
system location, which usually needs the root password to write to. If you are
working on someone else's machine or want to keep packages out of the system
python directory, you can ask `pip` to install to a specific directory under
your control, or to a default location in your `/home` directory (examples
follow).

You don't need to install `pip` -- if you have Python, you have `pip`.

---

### pip vs. conda

In the past almost everyone used `pip`. Now more people are using `conda`: one
problem with `conda` is that the learning curve is slightly steeper than `pip`,
because of the idea of 'environments' in `conda`. The advantage is that `conda`
can install a wider range of software, and can isolate everything very cleanly
from the version of Python used by the operating system. 

The advantage of `pip` is that it is less hassle and is more-or-less built in
to Python (`conda` has to be installed separately, almost always this is done
by installing Miniconda or another distribution that relies on `conda`).

Somewhat confusingly, it's common to create a `conda` environment and then
install packages into that environment using `pip`! It's hard to figure out the
best practice sometimes.

---

### To install packages with `pip`:

`pip install [name of package]`

Add the `--user` option if you don't have/want to use root access to install to
the system python directory.

You can also use the option `--prefix=/some/path/on/your/disk` to install a
package to a specific location. Remember that this location will have to be
included in your `PYTHONPATH` shell environment variable (or otherwise added into
the list `sys.path` by your Python code) before you can `import` the package.
`/some/path/on/your/disk` here *does not* include anything specific to the
package you're installing, so you should only need to add one such directory to
your `PYHTONPATH`. Example follows in a couple of slides.

---

### To install packages without a package manager

Some packages you will need to install yourself directly from code that you
download. In this case the usual convention for packages considered to be in a
reasonable state to distribute (i.e. not quick hacks from your colleagues) is
that a file `setup.py` will exist in the top-level directory of whatever you
download. This file will import some standard packages that provide a common
way to install Python programs -- all you need to do is run it with Python and
be aware of some standard options.


If you don't want to read the README for the package to figure out how to
install it, a usually good first guess is:

`python setup.py install --prefix=/some/path/on/your/disk`

Again, this path should be on your `PYTHONPATH`.

---

class: smallcode

For example: Say user `bravo` uses the `bash` shell and wants to put their
third-party python packages installed with `pip` in
`/home/bravobear/python/pip`, packages they install from github and elsewhere
in `/home/bravo/python/opt` and stuff they write themselves in
`/home/bravo/python/dev`.

In `.bash_profile` (or similar):

```bash
export PYTHONPATH=/home/bravo/python/pip/lib/python3.6/site-packages
export PYTHONPATH=/home/bravo/python/opt/lib/python3.6/site-packages:$PYTHONPATH
export PYTHONPATH=/home/bravo/python/dev:$PYTHONPATH
```

Then `pip install --prefix /home/bravo/python/pip/` will do the right thing.
The `lib/python3.6/site-packages` part is added automatically (if you know what this
means, `/home/bravo/python/pip/` is acting like `/usr/local`). (By the way, the `--user`
option to `pip` puts your packages in `~/.local`.)

---

### pip inside conda environments

If you're using `conda`, you should be able to `pip install` from inside a
`conda` environment and not worry to much about where the files are going.
That's the point of making a self-contained environment.

---

### To install packages with `conda`: 

`conda install [name of package]`

To make a `conda` environment called `myenvironment` that initially has the
packages `numpy`, `matplotlib` and `astropy` in it you can do:

`conda create myenvironment numpy matplotlib astropy`

Then you need to activate that environment when you work: `source activate
myenvironment`. The shell prompt will change to show you're working in that
environment. From that point on, you will be working with a Python executable
and set of Python packages that is isolated to that environment and under your
control, independent of any other environments and the system python. 

---

To list the packages available in the environment, you can do `conda list`. If
you install new packages inside an environment, they will only be available
inside that environment. You can have separate environments for Python 2,
Python 3 and any other particular version of Python you want. You can use `pip`
inside a `conda` environment too, and the effect will be to install the package
in that environment, not system-wide.

When you're finished working with that environment you can call `source
deactivate` to return to the normal system prompt.

This seems like a lot of hassle at first, but it does make things easier in the
long run.

---

### Non-python dependencies

Some python packages might depend on pre-compiled, non-Python code. For
example, the packages that work with the HDF5 format will require your system
to have the HDF5 libraries installed, and the `healpy` package requires the
`HEALPIX` libraries. `FITSIO` is another common one in astronomy.

---

Conda is particularly helpful in such cases because it can also install any
non-Python libraries and software that a given python package depends on and
maintain **different** versions of these in different conda environments. For
example, you can `conda install hdf5`.

`pip` only does this 'sometimes' for the bigger, better-supported packages (for
example, installing `numpy` involves compiling some well-tested,
high-performance numerical libraries written in C and Fortran, but this is
handled by `pip`). Both HDF5 and HEALPIX are handled by `pip`, but it isn't
very transparent how this happens or how those versions interact with others on
your system.

---

If you don't use `conda` but do use linux, then these external dependencies can
usually be installed easily system-wide with your package manager (maintaining
multiple versions, if you need to, is more difficult). For Macs there are
third-party package managers like [Homebrew](http://brew.sh/) to do the same
job. 

Conda will nearly always install these third-party libraries for you
automatically -- my suggestion is to use `conda` for an easy life.

---
